---
description: Enforce rich inline documentation to maximize AI embedding/indexing quality. Use for all TypeScript files.
globs: **/*.ts,**/*.tsx
alwaysApply: false
---

Goal: every code chunk must carry enough context for Cursor's embedding layer to understand its purpose, relationships, and usage — without needing to read surrounding files.

File-Level Header (required for every module):

- Start each file with a JSDoc block describing the module's responsibility
- Mention the bounded context / domain it belongs to
- List key exports and their roles

```typescript
/**
 * @module session-store-adapter
 * @description Redis-backed implementation of ISessionStore for the Auth bounded context.
 * Handles session persistence, TTL management, and cache invalidation.
 *
 * @see {@link ISessionStore} — port interface in domain/ports/
 * @see {@link HubSession} — entity stored by this adapter
 */
```

Function & Method Documentation:

- Always document the WHY (business intent), not just the WHAT
- Include `@param`, `@returns`, `@throws` for all public functions
- Use `@example` with realistic snippets — embeddings index these as usage patterns
- Use `@see` to link related symbols — helps the indexer build a navigation graph

```typescript
/**
 * Exchanges an authorization code for a Hub session.
 * Called after Keycloak redirect to establish the user's authenticated context.
 *
 * @param code - OAuth2 authorization code from Keycloak callback
 * @param redirectUri - The original redirect URI registered with the IdP
 * @returns A fully hydrated HubSession with tokens and user profile
 * @throws {AuthCodeExpiredError} When the code has already been consumed or timed out
 *
 * @example
 * ```typescript
 * const session = await loginUseCase.execute({
 *   code: 'abc123',
 *   redirectUri: 'https://hub.modelo.fr/callback',
 * });
 * ```
 *
 * @see {@link IAuthProvider.exchangeCode}
 * @see {@link HubSession}
 */
```

Interface & Type Documentation:

- Document every exported interface/type with its domain role
- Annotate each property — the indexer chunks at the property level
- Use `@see` to connect ports to their adapters and entities to their repositories

```typescript
/**
 * Port defining the contract for session persistence.
 * Implemented by RedisSessionStoreAdapter in infrastructure/.
 *
 * @see {@link RedisSessionStoreAdapter} — production implementation
 * @see {@link InMemorySessionStore} — test double
 */
export interface ISessionStore {
  /** Persists a session with automatic TTL. */
  save(session: HubSession): Promise<void>;

  /** Retrieves a session by its unique identifier, or null if expired/missing. */
  findById(id: SessionId): Promise<HubSession | null>;
}
```

Cross-Reference Tags (critical for navigation):

- `@see {@link Symbol}` — connects related symbols across files
- `@module` — names the module for the indexer
- `@remarks` — adds architectural context that survives chunking

Constants & Configuration:

- Document constants with their business meaning, not just their value
- Group related constants and explain the group's purpose

```typescript
/**
 * Maximum session duration before forced re-authentication.
 * Aligned with Keycloak realm SSO session idle timeout (ADR-007).
 */
export const SESSION_TTL_SECONDS = 28800;
```

Anti-Patterns:

- Avoid undocumented exports — invisible to the embedding layer
- Avoid orphan symbols — always `@see` at least one related type
- Avoid vague descriptions ("handles stuff") — be specific about domain intent
- Avoid documenting the obvious from the type signature — add business context instead